'''Lawrence "Larry" Anderson Ward''' ([[October 2]], [[1940s|1944]] - [[October 15]], [[2007]]) was an actor and linguist who developed the [[Huttese]] language alongside [[Ben Burtt]] on [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']]. He also provided the voice of both [[Greedo]] (in ''A New Hope'') and [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure|Jabba]] the [[Hutt]] (in [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']]).

==Biography==
By c. 1976 Larry Ward was graduate of linguistics from [[Wikipedia:University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]] and was familiar with eleven different languages.<ref name="travel">[[Galactic Phrase Book & Travel Guide (real-life book)|''Galactic Phrase Book & Travel Guide'']]</ref>

''[[Star Wars]]'' sound designer Ben Burtt had decided to use the sounds of [[Wikipedia:Quechuan languages|Quechua]] for the filmed dialogue with Greedo; having failed to find a speaker of Quechua, he discovered Ward, whose linguistic background allowed him to analyse sound samples, transcribe them, and familiarize himself with its sounds; thus he was able to repeat or read Quechua comfortably like a fluent speaker.<ref name="travel" />

In their sessions together, they chose their favorite sounds and invented their own "words" and sounds based on the phonetics of Quechua, which they recorded. Burtt wrote out "fake Quechua" phrases based on Greedo's snout movements on the scene, and timed with them.<ref name="travel" />

